<html><head><meta http-equiv="Content-Type" content="text/html; charset=utf-8" /><meta http-equiv="Content-Style-Type" content="text/css" /><meta name="generator" content="Aspose.Words for .NET 13.4.0.0" /><title>IPCC 5th Assessment Report Inquiry</title></head><body><div><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:10pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:140%; margin:0pt; text-align:center"><span style="font-family:Helvetica; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Written evidence submitted by Barry Brill (IPC0018)</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:140%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Helvetica; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:140%; margin:0pt; text-align:center"><span style="font-family:Helvetica; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:140%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Helvetica; font-size:12pt">Specific Terms of Reference addressed:</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:140%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Helvetica; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Helvetica; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic; line-height:110%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 13pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Helvetica; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">To what extent does AR5 reflect the range of views among climate scientists?</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:110%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Helvetica; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="2" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Helvetica; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic; line-height:110%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 13pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Helvetica; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">Does the AR5 address the reliability of climate models? </span></li></ol><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:110%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Helvetica; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="3" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Helvetica; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic; line-height:110%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 13pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Helvetica; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">Has AR5 sufficiently explained the reasons behind the reported hiatus in the global surface temperature record? </span></li></ol><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:110%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Helvetica; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="4" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Helvetica; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic; line-height:110%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 13pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Helvetica; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">Do the AR5 conclusions strengthen or weaken the economic case for action to prevent dangerous climate change? </span></li></ol><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:110%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Helvetica; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="5" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Helvetica; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic; line-height:110%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 13pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Helvetica; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">What implications do the AR5 conclusions have for policy making both nationally and internationally?</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:140%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Helvetica; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:140%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Helvetica; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:140%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Helvetica; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Summary of submissions:</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:140%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Helvetica; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><ol type="A" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Helvetica; font-size:12pt; line-height:140%; margin:0pt 0pt 12pt 14.65pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Helvetica; font-size:12pt">The most policy-</span><span style="font-family:Helvetica; font-size:12pt">relevant role of AR5 is to provide reliable projections of likely future global temperatures for the decades </span><span style="font-family:Helvetica; font-size:12pt">centred</span><span style="font-family:Helvetica; font-size:12pt"> on 2050 and 2090. </span></li><li style="font-family:Helvetica; font-size:12pt; line-height:140%; margin:0pt 0pt 12pt 14.65pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Helvetica; font-size:12pt">AR5 provides</span><a name="_ftnref1"></a><a href="#_ftn1">[1]</a><span style="font-family:Helvetica; font-size:12pt"> an unhelpfully wide spread of likely warming for 2090, extending from 0.4°C (benign) to 4.8°C (dangerous) </span><span style="font-family:Helvetica; font-size:12pt">relative to 1850 temperatures. In most instances, the 2°C limit </span><span style="font-family:Helvetica; font-size:12pt">favoured</span><span style="font-family:Helvetica; font-size:12pt"> by world Governments will be observed, and no policy response is required. The few dangerous cases are not clearly differentiated. </span></li><li style="font-family:Helvetica; font-size:12pt; line-height:140%; margin:0pt 0pt 12pt 14.65pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Helvetica; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Both WG1 and Government representatives </span><span style="font-family:Helvetica; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">recognise</span><a name="_ftnref2"></a><a href="#_ftn2">[2]</a><span style="font-family:Helvetica; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold"> </span><span style="font-family:Helvetica; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">that averaged CMIP5 temperature projections for the 21st century are unreliable and implausible. </span><span style="font-family:Helvetica; font-size:12pt">Remediation has arbitrarily (and wrongly) consisted of discounting the first third of the century, downgrading confidence in the second third and leaving the f</span><span style="font-family:Helvetica; font-size:12pt">inal third intact.</span></li><li style="font-family:Helvetica; font-size:12pt; line-height:140%; margin:0pt 0pt 12pt 14.65pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Helvetica; font-size:12pt">The two model inputs that materially determine AR5 values for future warming are (a) climate sensitivity and (b) the selected RCP. </span></li><li style="font-family:Helvetica; font-size:12pt; line-height:140%; margin:0pt 0pt 12pt 14.65pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Helvetica; font-size:12pt">For the first time, the IPCC finds itself unable to reach consensus on a ‘most likely’ sensitivity (ECS) </span><span style="font-family:Helvetica; font-size:12pt">figure. There are two distinct (and mutually exclusive) schools of thought at about 1.7°C and 3°C respectively. If the former group is correct (so the TCR is &lt;1.5°), virtually all warming projections become benign and policy action unjustified. </span></li><li style="font-family:Helvetica; font-size:12pt; line-height:140%; margin:0pt 0pt 12pt 14.65pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Helvetica; font-size:12pt">For the fi</span><span style="font-family:Helvetica; font-size:12pt">rst time, the future scenarios are hypothetical rather than probabilistic. The four RCPs cannot be aggregated or averaged, and it is left to the user (policymaker) to select the ‘most likely’ pathway. Observed forcing to date suggests that all four RCPs ar</span><span style="font-family:Helvetica; font-size:12pt">e over-stated. </span></li><li style="font-family:Helvetica; font-size:12pt; line-height:140%; margin:0pt 0pt 12pt 14.65pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Helvetica; font-size:12pt">RCP 4.5 should be viewed as the base case, with 2.6 and 6.0 respectively being the low and high cases. RCP 8.5 represents the very unlikely ‘abrupt climate change’ described in Table 12.4 of the WG1 report. </span></li><li style="font-family:Helvetica; font-size:12pt; line-height:140%; margin:0pt 0pt 12pt 14.65pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Helvetica; font-size:12pt">If a TCR of 1.5°C is adopted, RC</span><span style="font-family:Helvetica; font-size:12pt">P4.5 provides</span><a name="_ftnref3"></a><a href="#_ftn3">[3]</a><span style="font-family:Helvetica; font-size:12pt"> a warming range of 1.1 to 1.6°C. Deducting the 0.72°C that occurred pre-1999</span><a name="_ftnref4"></a><a href="#_ftn4">[4]</a><span style="font-family:Helvetica; font-size:12pt">, this leaves 0.38-0.88°C as the</span><span style="font-family:Helvetica; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic"> likely</span><span style="font-family:Helvetica; font-size:12pt"> temperature increase during the 21st century (midpoint less than the 20th century). </span></li><li style="font-family:Helvetica; font-size:12pt; line-height:140%; margin:0pt 0pt 12pt 11.67pt; padding-left:2.98pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Helvetica; font-size:12pt">If the most likely estimate of ECS prov</span><span style="font-family:Helvetica; font-size:12pt">es to be less than 2°C, AR5 </span><span style="font-family:Helvetica; font-size:12pt; text-decoration:underline">does not</span><span style="font-family:Helvetica; font-size:12pt"> project worrisome future warming, or sea level rise, except in the extreme case of RCP8.5. </span></li><li style="font-family:Helvetica; font-size:12pt; line-height:140%; margin:0pt 0pt 12pt 14.33pt; padding-left:0.32pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Helvetica; font-size:12pt">While the high-impact-low-probability RCP8.5 scenario cannot be ignored, it poses unique challenges for policymakers. In particular, the risks of such cataclysmic possibilities as </span><span style="font-family:Helvetica; font-size:12pt">clathrate</span><span style="font-family:Helvetica; font-size:12pt"> methane release or Atlantic MOC collapse are not well correlated w</span><span style="font-family:Helvetica; font-size:12pt">ith projected incremental warming. They most likely have other causes. </span></li><li style="font-family:Helvetica; font-size:12pt; line-height:140%; margin:0pt 0pt 12pt 14.65pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Helvetica; font-size:12pt">AR5 weakens and adds confusion to the economic case for policy action. Benefit-cost analyses cannot advance pending resolution of the stalemate over the most likely ECS value. This iss</span><span style="font-family:Helvetica; font-size:12pt">ue needs to be the subject of an IPCC special report. </span></li><li style="font-family:Helvetica; font-size:12pt; line-height:140%; margin:0pt 0pt 12pt 14.65pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Helvetica; font-size:12pt">The AR5 evaluation of CMIP5 models found most to be unreliable.  The appropriate response is to require the most errant group (say, up to the 8th </span><span style="font-family:Helvetica; font-size:12pt">decile</span><span style="font-family:Helvetica; font-size:12pt">) to be reprogrammed or tuned so as to accurately</span><span style="font-family:Helvetica; font-size:12pt"> simulate observations over the past 30 years. If they cannot, they must be excluded from future ensemble averages. Readings based upon pre-correction simulations (</span><span style="font-family:Helvetica; font-size:12pt">ie</span><span style="font-family:Helvetica; font-size:12pt"> AR5 ‘assessed’ projections) ought to be discarded. </span></li><li style="font-family:Helvetica; font-size:12pt; line-height:140%; margin:0pt 0pt 12pt 14.65pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Helvetica; font-size:12pt">The flat 20% discount  and the reduct</span><span style="font-family:Helvetica; font-size:12pt">ion of confidence levels were 11th-hour trade-offs, necessitated by WG1’s belated recognition that ‘the hiatus’ had </span><span style="font-family:Helvetica; font-size:12pt">embarassed</span><span style="font-family:Helvetica; font-size:12pt"> the models.</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:140%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Helvetica; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:140%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Helvetica; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Relating </span><span style="font-family:Helvetica; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">these </span><span style="font-family:Helvetica; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Submissions to </span><span style="font-family:Helvetica; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">the </span><span style="font-family:Helvetica; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Terms of Reference -</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:140%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Helvetica; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><ol type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Helvetica; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold; line-height:140%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 13pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Helvetica; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">AR5 temperature projections fail to reflect the current inte</span><span style="font-family:Helvetica; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">rnal</span><span style="font-family:Helvetica; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold"> IPCC</span><span style="font-family:Helvetica; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold"> disagreement regarding climate sensitivity and its contribution to ‘the hiatus’.</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:140%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Helvetica; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="2" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Helvetica; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold; line-height:140%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 13pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Helvetica; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold; text-decoration:underline">AR5 accepts that CMIP5 projections are unreliable – but arbitrarily toys with ensemble outputs, rather than excluding </span><span style="font-family:Helvetica; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold; text-decoration:underline">the </span><span style="font-family:Helvetica; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold; text-decoration:underline">incorrigible models.</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:140%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Helvetica; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="3" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Helvetica; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold; line-height:140%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 13pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Helvetica; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">AR5 is unable to </span><span style="font-family:Helvetica; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">identify/quantify the reasons for, or the duration of, ‘the hiatus’.</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:140%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Helvetica; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="4" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Helvetica; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold; line-height:140%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 13pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Helvetica; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">AR5 conclusions fatally weaken the economic case for policy action. Both the level of, and confidence in, temperature projections are sharply reduced. </span></li></ol><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:140%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Helvetica; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="5" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Helvetica; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold; line-height:140%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 13pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Helvetica; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold"> AR5 conclusions seriously inhibi</span><span style="font-family:Helvetica; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">t policy-making in that they withdraw the pr</span><span style="font-family:Helvetica; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">evious sensitivity guideline as well as</span><span style="font-family:Helvetica; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold"> the probabilistic scenarios. These are the major inputs to integrated assessment models (IAMs) which </span><span style="font-family:Helvetica; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">analyse</span><span style="font-family:Helvetica; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold"> the benefits of action to mitigate GHG emissions.</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:140%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Helvetica; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:140%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Helvetica; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Recommendati</span><span style="font-family:Helvetica; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">on: The IPCC should issue a special report on ECS and TCR values, cull </span><span style="font-family:Helvetica; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">non-performing models and publish</span><span style="font-family:Helvetica; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold"> a replacement high-confidence set of projections.</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:140%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Helvetica; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:140%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Helvetica; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:140%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Helvetica; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:140%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Helvetica; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:140%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Helvetica; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:140%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Helvetica; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:140%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Helvetica; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Introduction</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:140%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Helvetica; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:140%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Helvetica; font-size:12pt">The IPCC Assessment reports inform Governments on many climate-related issues at multiple levels, but their core raison </span><span style="font-family:Helvetica; font-size:12pt">d’etre</span><span style="font-family:Helvetica; font-size:12pt"> is to estimate the amplitude and pace of future global warming, and the implications thereof for world governments. </span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:140%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Helvetica; font-size:12pt">This objecti</span><span style="font-family:Helvetica; font-size:12pt">ve is pursued by sifting and interpreting current scientific literature relevant to the operation of an ensemble (CMIP5) of coupled ocean-atmosphere climate models (AO-GCMs) which translate anticipated quantities of greenhouse gases (GHGs) into estimates o</span><span style="font-family:Helvetica; font-size:12pt">f anthropogenic global warming (AGW) and its climatic consequences. </span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:140%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Helvetica; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:140%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Helvetica; font-size:12pt">An observed percentage of GHG emissions adds to the atmospheric concentration (in </span><span style="font-family:Helvetica; font-size:12pt">ppm</span><span style="font-family:Helvetica; font-size:12pt"> of CO2-e), which drives the </span><span style="font-family:Helvetica; font-size:12pt">radiative</span><span style="font-family:Helvetica; font-size:12pt"> forcing (RF) that creates an initial warming (in °C). This pro</span><span style="font-family:Helvetica; font-size:12pt">duces positive and negative feedbacks, the net effect of which determines the extent of any AGW contribution to increases in the average global surface temperature anomaly (GASTA). </span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:140%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Helvetica; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:140%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Helvetica; font-size:12pt">Equilibrium climate sensitivity (ECS) is the eventual overall change in G</span><span style="font-family:Helvetica; font-size:12pt">ASTA brought about by a doubling of atmospheric CO2-e, while transient climate response (TCR) measures the short-term (</span><span style="font-family:Helvetica; font-size:12pt">ie</span><span style="font-family:Helvetica; font-size:12pt"> 20-year) change. Although reducing the lower bounds for likely ECS and TCR, AR5 was unable to agree upon a ‘best estimate’ of either. </span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:140%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Helvetica; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:140%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Helvetica; font-size:12pt">The AR5 introduced the concept of representative concentration pathways (RCPs), which comprise four hypothetical RF levels, with conjectural GHG/aerosol emission trajectories (plus land use) over the period 2015-2100. </span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:140%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Helvetica; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:140%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Helvetica; font-size:12pt">Shorn of the endless complications</span><span style="font-family:Helvetica; font-size:12pt"> and distractions occupying over 2000 pages of the WG1 report, future AGW is driven by two key inputs – a TCR level and a preferred RCP. The expected 2090 AGW depends crucially on the enquirer’s choices of these two determinants from amongst the respective</span><span style="font-family:Helvetica; font-size:12pt"> ranges offered by the IPCC.  </span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:140%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Helvetica; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:140%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Helvetica; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Sensitivity </span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:140%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Helvetica; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:140%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Helvetica; font-size:12pt">Driven by the need to explain the unexpected temperature ‘hiatus’, the value of ECS has been a major focus of climate scientists during the past two years. </span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:140%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Helvetica; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:13pt; line-height:140%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Helvetica; font-size:12pt">ECS was crudely</span><a name="_ftnref5"></a><a href="#_ftn5">[5]</a><span style="font-family:Helvetica; font-size:12pt"> estimated by </span><span style="font-family:Helvetica; font-size:13pt">Charney</span><span style="font-family:Helvetica; font-size:12pt"> in 1979 at 3.0</span><span style="font-family:Helvetica; font-size:12pt"> ±1.5°C and that range remained more-or-less constant through all four previous IPCC reports.  </span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:140%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Helvetica; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:140%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Helvetica; font-size:12pt">However, during 2011-13, at least 16 peer-reviewed journal papers have used recent data and modern diagnostics to show that this historical ‘best estimate’ had been grossly over-stated. All find that the ‘most likely’ ECS figure is around 1.5-2°C – and lik</span><span style="font-family:Helvetica; font-size:12pt">ely to be within a range of 1-3.5°C (not 1.5-4.5°C as applied in AR5). </span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:140%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Helvetica; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:140%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Helvetica; font-size:12pt">After the March cut-off date for WG1 papers, the following 2013 papers have strongly reinforced concerns regarding the exaggeration of climate sensitivity: </span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:140%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 37.35pt; text-indent:-9pt"><span style="font-family:Helvetica; font-size:12pt; vertical-align:-1pt">•</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Helvetica; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">Otto et al:</span><span style="font-family:Helvetica; font-size:12pt"> the best estim</span><span style="font-family:Helvetica; font-size:12pt">ate of sensitivity is 30% below the CMIP5 mean. </span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:140%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 37.35pt; text-indent:-9pt"><span style="font-family:Helvetica; font-size:12pt; vertical-align:-1pt">•</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Helvetica; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">Forster et al:</span><span style="font-family:Helvetica; font-size:12pt"> analysis of CMIP5 shows that 2/3 are above the Otto ‘likely’ range. </span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:140%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 37.35pt; text-indent:-9pt"><span style="font-family:Helvetica; font-size:12pt; vertical-align:-1pt">•</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Helvetica; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">Masters</span><span style="font-family:Helvetica; font-size:12pt">: the median estimate of ECS is 1.98°C. </span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:140%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 37.35pt; text-indent:-9pt"><span style="font-family:Helvetica; font-size:12pt; vertical-align:-1pt">•</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Helvetica; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">Lewis:</span><span style="font-family:Helvetica; font-size:12pt">  improved methodology shows the mode and median to be 1.6°C.</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:140%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Helvetica; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:140%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Helvetica; font-size:12pt">Leaked</span><span style="font-family:Helvetica; font-size:12pt"> draft reports indicate much disputation within the IPCC about acceptance of the new and lower sensitivity figures, given that the Stockholm meeting was too late to impact coherently upon the widely-circulated drafts of CMIP5 projections. The final trade-o</span><span style="font-family:Helvetica; font-size:12pt">ffs were: </span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:140%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 42.35pt; text-indent:-14pt"><span style="font-family:Helvetica; font-size:12pt">(i)</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Helvetica; font-size:12pt">No consensus regarding the best estimate of ECS or TCR;</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:140%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 42.35pt; text-indent:-14pt"><span style="font-family:Helvetica; font-size:12pt">(ii)</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'"> </span><span style="font-family:Helvetica; font-size:12pt"> The lower bound for likely ECS range was lowered by 25% to 1.5°C; </span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:140%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 42.35pt; text-indent:-14pt"><span style="font-family:Helvetica; font-size:12pt">(iii)</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Helvetica; font-size:12pt"> The estimated TCR range was lowered by 20% to 1-2.5°C; </span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:140%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 42.35pt; text-indent:-14pt"><span style="font-family:Helvetica; font-size:12pt">(iv)</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Helvetica; font-size:12pt"> The ensemble temperature projections were discounted by 20% for the near-term 2016-35 period</span><a name="_ftnref6"></a><a href="#_ftn6">[6]</a><span style="font-family:Helvetica; font-size:12pt">, whilst the pre-Stockholm figures were otherwise retained; </span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:140%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 42.35pt; text-indent:-14pt"><span style="font-family:Helvetica; font-size:12pt">(v)</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Helvetica; font-size:12pt"> Confidence in the mid-term 2046-65 projections was downgraded to ‘medium’.</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:140%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Helvetica; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:140%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Helvetica; font-size:12pt">Consequently, the projec</span><span style="font-family:Helvetica; font-size:12pt">tions appearing in Table SPM.2 do not reflect the TCR parameter now recommended in the WG1 report. In a word, they are incorrect. The AR5 is not internally consistent. </span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:140%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Helvetica; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:140%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Helvetica; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Reliability of Climate Models</span><span style="font-family:Helvetica; font-size:12pt"> </span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:140%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Helvetica; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:140%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Helvetica; font-size:12pt">As with any mathematical model, the outputs from CMIP5</span><span style="font-family:Helvetica; font-size:12pt"> are determined by their programmed axioms, postulates and assumptions in addition to their data inputs. Many of these are uncertain and some are the subject of longstanding disputes. The reliability of any GCM is therefore wholly dependent on its proven p</span><span style="font-family:Helvetica; font-size:12pt">redictive ability.</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:140%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Helvetica; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:140%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Helvetica; font-size:12pt">However, for reasons of comity and politics, there are no standards or other entry barriers for models joining the CMIP5. Some have ECS postulants higher than the 3°C ‘most likely’ historical guideline. Although many are wholly unable to </span><span style="font-family:Helvetica; font-size:12pt">hindcast</span><span style="font-family:Helvetica; font-size:12pt"> recent ob</span><span style="font-family:Helvetica; font-size:12pt">served temperatures or precipitation, they have not been </span><span style="font-family:Helvetica; font-size:12pt">penalised</span><span style="font-family:Helvetica; font-size:12pt"> on that account. </span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:140%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Helvetica; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:140%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Helvetica; font-size:12pt">The IPCC models did not forecast ‘the hiatus’, and were not even close. </span><span style="font-family:Helvetica; font-size:12pt; text-decoration:underline">All published model projections since the 1988 Hansen model have seriously over-estimated the actu</span><span style="font-family:Helvetica; font-size:12pt; text-decoration:underline">al warming of the past 25 years. </span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:140%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Helvetica; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:140%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Helvetica; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">Fyfe Gillett &amp; </span><span style="font-family:Helvetica; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">Zwiers</span><a name="_ftnref7"></a><a href="#_ftn7">[7]</a><span style="font-family:Helvetica; font-size:12pt"> recently reported in </span><span style="font-family:Helvetica; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">Nature Climate Science </span><span style="font-family:Helvetica; font-size:12pt">on the extraordinary gap between the temperature simulations of 37 CIMP5 models and the observed data. Due to a ‘combination of errors’, the models have o</span><span style="font-family:Helvetica; font-size:12pt">verestimated warming by 100% over the past 20 years and by 400% over the past 15 years.   [NOTE: All three authors are senior IPCC authors or vice-chairmen]. </span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:140%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Helvetica; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:140%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Helvetica; font-size:12pt">SPM.2 (Note (c)) reveals that the</span><span style="font-family:Helvetica; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic"> “assessed range for near-term (2016-2035) temperature change” </span><span style="font-family:Helvetica; font-size:12pt">(</span><span style="font-family:Helvetica; font-size:12pt">ie</span><span style="font-family:Helvetica; font-size:12pt"> final projections)</span><span style="font-family:Helvetica; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic"> “is lower than the 5-95% model range”.</span><span style="font-family:Helvetica; font-size:12pt"> This obscure comment is the sole SPM disclosure that all of the CMIP5 near-term projections were downscaled by an arbitrary 20% at the Stockholm meeting. This was necessary to belatedly </span><span style="font-family:Helvetica; font-size:12pt">recognis</span><span style="font-family:Helvetica; font-size:12pt">e</span><span style="font-family:Helvetica; font-size:12pt"> that many of the models are “running hot”</span><a name="_ftnref8"></a><a href="#_ftn8">[8]</a><span style="font-family:Helvetica; font-size:12pt"> and are wholly incompatible with temperature realities.</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:140%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Helvetica; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:140%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Helvetica; font-size:12pt">This band-aid was neither scientific nor rational. When certain models are wildly astray, the only acceptable procedure is to isolate all ensembles affect</span><span style="font-family:Helvetica; font-size:12pt">ed by their outputs and to require the culprits to be adjusted. If they remain unable to </span><span style="font-family:Helvetica; font-size:12pt">hindcast</span><span style="font-family:Helvetica; font-size:12pt"> ‘the real world’, they must obviously be set aside. </span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:140%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Helvetica; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:140%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Helvetica; font-size:12pt">A last-minute curve-correcting discount of all model outputs for a limited and arbitrary period </span><span style="font-family:Helvetica; font-size:12pt">inevitably smacks of panic. The unapologetic ad </span><span style="font-family:Helvetica; font-size:12pt">hockery</span><span style="font-family:Helvetica; font-size:12pt"> of this intervention undermines the </span><span style="font-family:Helvetica; font-size:12pt">plausibilty</span><span style="font-family:Helvetica; font-size:12pt"> of all AR5 projections.</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:140%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Helvetica; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:140%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Helvetica; font-size:12pt">The sudden necessity of a 20% discount seriously impeaches the SPM assertion that past attribution certainty has increased to a</span><span style="font-family:Helvetica; font-size:12pt"> 95% level. </span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:140%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Helvetica; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:140%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Helvetica; font-size:12pt">Such alleged certainty contrasts with confidence in the mid-term (2046-65) future projections being marked down to “medium” – meaning about a 50:50 chance of being correct, or ‘as likely as not’ to be wrong. This is markedly lower than any pr</span><span style="font-family:Helvetica; font-size:12pt">evious IPCC projections. </span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:140%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Helvetica; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:140%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Helvetica; font-size:12pt">The confidence markdown was made because there is “insufficient scientific understanding” whether “the factors” that caused the 20% discount of near-term projections, might also apply to the mid-term</span><a name="_ftnref9"></a><a href="#_ftn9">[9]</a><span style="font-family:Helvetica; font-size:12pt">. </span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:140%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Helvetica; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:140%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Helvetica; font-size:12pt">50:50 estimates of discre</span><span style="font-family:Helvetica; font-size:12pt">dited models using obsolete postulants and ‘insufficient understanding’, cannot hope to provide an adequate basis for worldwide epoch-changing policy decisions. </span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:140%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Helvetica; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:140%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Helvetica; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:140%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Helvetica; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Cause of the pause</span><span style="font-family:Helvetica; font-size:12pt"> </span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:140%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Helvetica; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:140%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Helvetica; font-size:12pt">Despite obscure language, the SPM accepts that the 1998-2012 warming of</span><span style="font-family:Helvetica; font-size:12pt"> 0.05±0.15°C was not significant, and that a cooling trend (also insignificant) has obtained throughout the 21st Century. Both trends discredit the CMIP3 and CMIP5 climate models, which have consistently projected warming of 2-3°C/decade throughout this pe</span><span style="font-family:Helvetica; font-size:12pt">riod. </span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:140%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Helvetica; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:140%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Helvetica; font-size:12pt">In August 2013, IPPC lead author Dr Hans von </span><span style="font-family:Helvetica; font-size:12pt">Storch</span><span style="font-family:Helvetica; font-size:12pt">, told </span><span style="font-family:Helvetica; font-size:12pt">Speigel</span><span style="font-family:Helvetica; font-size:12pt"> Online</span><a name="_ftnref10"></a><a href="#_ftn10">[10]</a><span style="font-family:Helvetica; font-size:12pt">: </span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:140%; margin:0pt"><span style="color:#666666; font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">“So far, no one has been able to provide a compelling answer to why climate change</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:140%; margin:0pt"><span style="color:#666666; font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">seems to be taking a break....  There are two conceivable explanations -- and neither is </span><span style="color:#666666; font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">very pleasant for us. The first possibility is that less global warming is occurring than expected because greenhouse gases, especially CO2, have less of an effect than we have assumed. ... The other possibility is that, in our simulations, we have underes</span><span style="color:#666666; font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">timated how much the climate fluctuates owing to natural causes.</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:140%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Helvetica; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:140%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Helvetica; font-size:12pt">At Stockholm, no AR5 consensus could be reached on the first and most obvious explanation – exaggerated sensitivity. </span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:140%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Helvetica; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:140%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Helvetica; font-size:12pt">The AR5 did accept that it had under-estimated natural climate variability. This was supported by a subsequent model-based </span><span style="font-family:Helvetica; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">Nature</span><span style="font-family:Helvetica; font-size:12pt"> paper</span><a name="_ftnref11"></a><a href="#_ftn11">[11]</a><span style="font-family:Helvetica; font-size:12pt"> showing that ENSO cooling activity in the East Pacific could have conquered AGW effects subsequent to the PDO negative </span><span style="font-family:Helvetica; font-size:12pt">shift</span><a name="_ftnref12"></a><a href="#_ftn12">[12]</a><span style="font-family:Helvetica; font-size:12pt"> in about 2002. The corollary is that the 0.68°C warming trend during 1975-98 (when the PDO was positive) would have been</span><a name="_ftnref13"></a><a href="#_ftn13">[13]</a><span style="font-family:Helvetica; font-size:12pt"> 0.4°C natural and only 0.28°C anthropogenic. </span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:140%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Helvetica; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:140%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Helvetica; font-size:12pt">If the PDO could deliver such definitive temperature effects during the past 40 </span><span style="font-family:Helvetica; font-size:12pt">years, why is this ignored in the AR5 forward projections for the next 40 years? </span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:140%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Helvetica; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:140%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Helvetica; font-size:12pt">The SPM’s reasoning regarding the imminent end-point of ‘the hiatus’ is unconvincing.  Most solar scientists predict a further 30 years for the low-activity cycle and PDO/AM</span><span style="font-family:Helvetica; font-size:12pt">O periodicity supports similar timing. The SPM group presumably </span><span style="font-family:Helvetica; font-size:12pt">recognised</span><span style="font-family:Helvetica; font-size:12pt"> that political and public support will likely be devastated if ‘the hiatus’ continues for a further 2-3 years.  </span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:140%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Helvetica; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:140%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Helvetica; font-size:12pt">The evidence-free conjecture that AGW during ‘the hiatus’ might hav</span><span style="font-family:Helvetica; font-size:12pt">e been transported to the deep oceans, was not supported by AR5. The </span><span style="font-family:Helvetica; font-size:12pt">paleoclimate</span><span style="font-family:Helvetica; font-size:12pt"> record suggests that such heat storage would remain operative for thousands of years, having no effect on GASTA. </span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:140%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Helvetica; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:140%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Helvetica; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">RCPs</span><span style="font-family:Helvetica; font-size:12pt"> </span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:140%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Helvetica; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:140%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Helvetica; font-size:12pt">AR5 does not suggest that any of the new RCPs are pr</span><span style="font-family:Helvetica; font-size:12pt">obable scenarios or forecasts. They are purely </span><span style="font-family:Helvetica; font-size:12pt">hypotheticals</span><span style="font-family:Helvetica; font-size:12pt">. </span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:140%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Helvetica; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:140%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Helvetica; font-size:12pt">Unlike the 2000 SRES, they do not cover all likely futures and are not equally probable. They use different assumptions, so cannot be summed or averaged. The IPPC effectively disclaims having </span><span style="font-family:Helvetica; font-size:12pt">any greater insight into future emissions than its member Governments and leaves it to users to select the RCP which they find the most probable. </span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:140%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Helvetica; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:140%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Helvetica; font-size:12pt">Most would regard RCP4.5 as the base case with higher and lower bounds provided by 6.0 and 2.6 respectively.</span><span style="font-family:Helvetica; font-size:12pt"> 8.5 covers the low-probability, high-impact ‘abrupt climate change’ case. </span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:140%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Helvetica; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:140%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Helvetica; font-size:12pt">The 4.5 base case mid-point (presumably the IPCC ‘best guess’) is 1.8°C, which is about equal to a forward projection of the observed temperature trend since the end of the Little</span><span style="font-family:Helvetica; font-size:12pt"> Ice Age (0.72°C/century). Under this central estimate:</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:140%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 37.35pt; text-indent:-9pt"><span style="font-family:Helvetica; font-size:12pt; vertical-align:-1pt">•</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Helvetica; font-size:12pt">the targeted 2°C limit will be achieved without intervention;</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:140%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 37.35pt; text-indent:-9pt"><span style="font-family:Helvetica; font-size:12pt; vertical-align:-1pt">•</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Helvetica; font-size:12pt">the Social Cost of Carbon (SCC) measured to 2100 will be negative (see below);</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:140%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 37.35pt; text-indent:-9pt"><span style="font-family:Helvetica; font-size:12pt; vertical-align:-1pt">•</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Helvetica; font-size:12pt">sea level rise estimated at 0.47m/century is rather more </span><span style="font-family:Helvetica; font-size:12pt">controversial, but still quite manageable;</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:140%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 37.35pt; text-indent:-9pt"><span style="font-family:Helvetica; font-size:12pt; vertical-align:-1pt">•</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Helvetica; font-size:12pt">it suggests that policy interventions should be confined to ‘no regrets’ adaptation; a</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:140%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 37.35pt; text-indent:-9pt"><span style="font-family:Helvetica; font-size:12pt; vertical-align:-1pt">•</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Helvetica; font-size:12pt">any potential ‘insurance’ against abrupt climate change should be </span><span style="font-family:Helvetica; font-size:12pt">costed</span><span style="font-family:Helvetica; font-size:12pt"> in accord with normal actuarial principles.</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:140%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Helvetica; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:140%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Helvetica; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">The Econ</span><span style="font-family:Helvetica; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">omic Case</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:140%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Helvetica; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:140%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Helvetica; font-size:12pt">In his review of the 14 published economic analyses, Professor </span><span style="font-family:Helvetica; font-size:12pt">Tol</span><span style="font-family:Helvetica; font-size:12pt"> (2009) shows</span><a name="_ftnref14"></a><a href="#_ftn14">[14]</a><span style="font-family:Helvetica; font-size:12pt"> that net welfare is enhanced by global warming until temperatures rise about 3°C from pre-industrial times (2.2°C from the present).</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:140%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Helvetica; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:140%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Helvetica; font-size:12pt">However, because incremental i</span><span style="font-family:Helvetica; font-size:12pt">mpacts may turn negative from about 2°C, it is argued that a “social cost of carbon” (SCC) arises from that point. Whether this externality justifies policy action depends on the costs of the </span><span style="font-family:Helvetica; font-size:12pt">intervention.As</span><span style="font-family:Helvetica; font-size:12pt"> averted damages and costs must both be discounte</span><span style="font-family:Helvetica; font-size:12pt">d back to present values, impacts reduce in direct proportion to delay. </span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:140%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Helvetica; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:140%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Helvetica; font-size:12pt">AR5 recognition of ‘the hiatus’ affects the economic case in four ways: </span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:140%; margin:0pt 0pt 12pt 42.35pt; text-indent:-14pt"><span style="font-family:Helvetica; font-size:12pt">(i)</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Helvetica; font-size:12pt">All previous linear projections (including AR5) need to be pushed into the future by 16 years –</span><span style="font-family:Helvetica; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span><span style="font-family:Helvetica; font-size:12pt">plus any addi</span><span style="font-family:Helvetica; font-size:12pt">tional period ‘the hiatus’ may continue; </span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:140%; margin:0pt 0pt 12pt 42.35pt; text-indent:-14pt"><span style="font-family:Helvetica; font-size:12pt">(ii)</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'"> </span><span style="font-family:Helvetica; font-size:12pt"> The new lower TCR range needs to be applied to the projections – which will delay the 2°C target point beyond 2100 in all three mainstream RCPs;  </span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:140%; margin:0pt 0pt 12pt 42.35pt; text-indent:-14pt"><span style="font-family:Helvetica; font-size:12pt">(iii)</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Helvetica; font-size:12pt"> During ‘the hiatus’, AGW offsets global cooling instead of causin</span><span style="font-family:Helvetica; font-size:12pt">g net global warming. This reversal of the counterfactual requires a wholesale re-calculation of the net damages examined by WG2. That has not yet occurred.</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:140%; margin:0pt 0pt 12pt 42.35pt; text-indent:-14pt"><span style="font-family:Helvetica; font-size:12pt">(iv)</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Helvetica; font-size:12pt"> The arbitrary ‘assessed’ 80% level for near-term, and ‘medium’ confidence for mid-term projections, will greatly amplify all discounts for uncertainty.</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:140%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Helvetica; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:140%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Helvetica; font-size:12pt">Prior to AR5, IAMs presumed the 40 SRES scenarios were equally probable and provided exhaustive covera</span><span style="font-family:Helvetica; font-size:12pt">ge of future possibilities. That is not possible with the RCPs, which will each need to be assigned a percentage probability. </span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:140%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt"><span style="font-family:Helvetica; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:140%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Helvetica; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Personal</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:140%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Helvetica; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:140%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Helvetica; font-size:12pt">I make these submissions as an individual with a lengthy background in energy policy issues. I was formerly a Ministe</span><span style="font-family:Helvetica; font-size:12pt">r of Science, and of Energy, in the New Zealand Government.</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:140%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Helvetica; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:140%; margin:0pt 0pt 12pt"><span style="font-family:Times; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">December 2013</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:140%; margin:0pt 0pt 12pt"><span style="font-family:Helvetica; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:140%; margin:0pt 0pt 12pt"><span style="font-family:Times; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:140%; margin:0pt 0pt 12pt"><span style="font-family:Times; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:10pt">&#xa0;</span></p></div><hr style="width:33%; height:1px; text-align:left" /><p style="margin:0pt"><a name="_ftn1"></a><a href="#_ftnref1">[1]</a><span style="font-family:Helvetica; font-size:10pt"> SPM p25, Table SPM.2</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><a name="_ftn2"></a><a href="#_ftnref2">[2]</a><span style="font-family:Helvetica; font-size:10pt"> At the Stockholm meeting in September 2013</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><a name="_ftn3"></a><a href="#_ftnref3">[3]</a><span style="font-family:Helvetica; font-size:10pt"> Table SPM.2 with the high TCR values (the upper 2/3rds) omitted.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><a name="_ftn4"></a><a href="#_ftnref4">[4]</a><span style="font-family:Helvetica; font-size:10pt"> See Note (a) Table SPM.2</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><a name="_ftn5"></a><a href="#_ftnref5">[5]</a><span style="font-family:Helvetica; font-size:10pt"> </span><a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Climate_sensitivity"><span style="color:#000099; font-family:Helvetica; font-size:10pt; text-decoration:underline">http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Cl</span><span style="color:#000099; font-family:Helvetica; font-size:10pt; text-decoration:underline">imate_sensitivity</span></a></p><p style="margin:0pt"><a name="_ftn6"></a><a href="#_ftnref6">[6]</a><span style="font-family:Helvetica; font-size:10pt"> Note (c) SPM.2. Model ranges are shown as likely “</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; font-style:italic">after accounting for additional uncertainties or different levels of confidence in models”</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">. As a result of the hiatus, and the fact that some models were obviously over-sensitive to </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">GHGs, it was considered prudent to reduce 2016-2035 model outputs by a flat 20%.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><a name="_ftn7"></a><a href="#_ftnref7">[7]</a><span style="font-family:Helvetica; font-size:10pt"> </span><a href="http://www.nature.com/nclimate/journal/v3/n9/full/nclimate1972.html?WT.ec_id=NCLIMATE-201309"><span style="color:#000099; font-family:Helvetica; font-size:10pt; font-style:italic; text-decoration:underline">http://www.nature.com/nclimate/journal/v3/n9/full/nclimate1972.html</span><span style="color:#000099; font-family:Helvetica; font-size:10pt; font-style:italic; text-decoration:underline">?WT.ec_id=NCLIMATE-201309</span></a></p><p style="margin:0pt"><a name="_ftn8"></a><a href="#_ftnref8">[8]</a><span style="font-family:Helvetica; font-size:10pt"> Press Conference wording reduced in the final SPM to “</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">in some models, an overestimate of </span><span style="font-family:Helvetica; font-size:10pt; font-style:italic">the response to increasing greenhouse gas and other anthropogenic forcing (dominated by the effects of aerosols)”.</span><span style="font-family:Helvetica; font-size:10pt"> {Box 10.2, 11.3}</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><a name="_ftn9"></a><a href="#_ftnref9">[9]</a><span style="font-family:Helvetica; font-size:10pt"> No</span><span style="font-family:Helvetica; font-size:10pt">te (c) SPM.2</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><a name="_ftn10"></a><a href="#_ftnref10">[10]</a><span style="font-family:Helvetica; font-size:10pt"> </span><a href="http://to"><span style="color:#000099; font-family:Arial; font-size:9pt; text-decoration:underline">http://to</span></a><span style="color:#026ada; font-family:Arial; font-size:9pt"> </span><span style="color:#026ada; font-family:Arial; font-size:9pt">mnelso</span><span style="color:#026ada; font-family:Arial; font-size:9pt"> n.blogspot.ae/2013/06/climate-scientist-hans-von-storch.html</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><a name="_ftn11"></a><a href="#_ftnref11">[11]</a><span style="font-family:Helvetica; font-size:10pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Helvetica; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">Yu </span><span style="font-family:Helvetica; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">Kosaka</span><span style="font-family:Helvetica; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic"> &amp; Shang-Ping </span><span style="font-family:Helvetica; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">Zie</span><span style="font-family:Helvetica; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic"> (August 2013)</span><span style="font-family:Helvetica; font-size:8pt; vertical-align:super"> </span><span style="font-family:Helvetica; font-size:10pt"> </span><a href="http://www.nature.com/nature/journal/vaop/ncurrent/full/nature12534.html"><span style="color:#000099; font-family:Helvetica; font-size:10pt; text-decoration:underline">http://www.nature.com/nature/journal/vaop/ncurrent/full/nature12534.html</span></a></p><p style="margin:0pt"><a name="_ftn12"></a><a href="#_ftnref12">[12]</a><span style="font-family:Helvetica; font-size:10pt"> The Pacific Decadal Oscillation is either positive (tendency to El Nino conditions) or negative (La Nina tendency) and switches at intervals of approximately 30 years.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><a name="_ftn13"></a><a href="#_ftnref13">[13]</a><span style="font-family:Helvetica; font-size:10pt">  See </span><a href="http://judithcurry.com/2013/08/28/pause-tied-to-equatorial-pacific-surface-cooling"><span style="color:#000099; font-family:Helvetica; font-size:10pt; text-decoration:underline">http://judithcurry.com/2013/08/28/pause-tied-to-equatorial-pacific-surface-cooling</span></a><span style="font-family:Helvetica; font-size:10pt"> </span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><a name="_ftn14"></a><a href="#_ftnref14">[14]</a><span style="font-family:Helvetica; font-size:10pt">  Richard </span><span style="font-family:Helvetica; font-size:10pt">Tol</span><span style="font-family:Helvetica; font-size:10pt">: “The Economic Effects of Climate Change” (2009) </span><span style="font-family:Helvetica; font-size:10pt; font-style:italic">Journal of E</span><span style="font-family:Helvetica; font-size:10pt; font-style:italic">conomic Perspectives 23.2</span><span style="font-family:Helvetica; font-size:10pt"> pp29-51. See Graph at Figure 1 p35.</span></p></body></html>